 \setcounter{enumi}{1}
Ensemble Empirical Mode Decomposition:- The ensemble empirical mode decomposition enhances the traditional EMD by adding white noise to the signals and averaging multiple decompositions. This approach of noise-assisted elimination of mode mixing produces more stable Intrinsic Mode Functions and is highly effective for analyzing nonlinear and non-stationary signals such as EEG data [16].

where $\epsilon_{i}(t)$ is the added white noise.
\begin{equation*}
x_{i}(t)=\sum_{k=1}^{K} c_{i k}(t)+r_{i K}(t)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

The final IMF is the ensemble mean:
\begin{equation*}
c_{k}(t)=\frac{1}{N} \sum_{i=1}^{N} c_{i k}(t)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where:
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
N=\text { number of ensemble trials, } \\
c_{k}(t)=k^{\text {th }} \text { Intrinsic Mode Function (IMF), } \\
r_{K}(t)=\text { final residue. }
\end{gathered}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}


 \setcounter{enumi}{2}
Entropy-Based Features: Entropy is a measure of the complexity and irregularity of the EEG signals as a measure of neural adaptability and information processing efficiency. Well-known ones are Permutation Entropy, Spectral Entropy, and Wavelet Entropy, which assess the unpredictability of the signal, the frequency distribution and the energy dispersion, respectively. Higher entropy indicates better cognitive flexibility and awareness in mindfulness analysis and lower entropy is indicative of stress, distracting or less attentional stability. The entropy characteristics offer a strong foundation on which one can tell the difference between mindful and non-mindful brain states.

where:-
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
P_{i}=\frac{S\left(f_{i}\right)}{\sum_{j=1}^{N} S\left(f_{j}\right)} \\
S\left(f_{i}\right)=\text { power spectral density at frequency } f_{i} \\
N=\text { number of frequency bins. }
\end{gathered}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
W E=-\sum_{j=1}^{J} p_{j} \ln p_{j}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where:-
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
p_{j}=\frac{E_{j}}{\sum_{k=1}^{J} E_{k}}, \\
E_{j}=\text { energy of wavelet coefficients at level } j, \\
J=\text { total number of decomposition levels. }
\end{gathered}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
P E(m, \tau)=-\sum_{i=1}^{m!} p\left(\pi_{i}\right) \ln p\left(\pi_{i}\right)
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}

Where:-
\begin{equation*}
\begin{gathered}
m=\text { embedding dimension, } \\
\tau=\text { time delay, } \\
p\left(\pi_{i}\right)=\text { probability of each ordinal pattern } \pi_{i}
\end{gathered}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}


 \setcounter{enumi}{3}
EEG Spectral Power of IMFs: After EEMD has been applied, spectral power of each Intrinsic Mode Function (IMF) is a reflection of the distribution of neural energy in different frequency bands. Normally, theta power is elevated on occasions of relaxation and concentrated attention whereas, the beta power is elevated when one is alert and stressed. The comparison of the spectral power in mindfulness and nonmindfulness conditions indicates that particular brain rhythms are predominant, with mindfulness being the state of the balanced and coherent neural activities in the theta and beta frequencies. The spectral power of the $k^{\text {th }}$ IMF is given as:

or in discrete form:
\begin{equation*}
P_{k}=\sum_{i=1}^{N}\left|C_{k}\left(f_{i}\right)\right|^{2}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
where
\begin{equation*}
C_{k}(f)=\text { Fourier transform of IMF } c_{k}(t),
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& P_{k}=\text { total power of the } k^{\text {th }} \text { IMF, and } \\
& f_{1}, f_{2}=\text { frequency range of interest. }
\end{aligned}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
